The shrine was founded on April 20, 2000 and serves to pray for the safe passage of all boats through the Senkaku Islands and the [[:en:East China Sea|East China Sea]]. Construction was led by [[Nihon Seinensha]], a right-wing organization affiliated with the [[Sumiyoshi-kai]], and wooden ''[[:en:Hokora|Hokora]]'' were also constructed. When the shrine was founded, it was the first time since the [[:en:End of World War II in Asia|end of World War II]] that a ''[[kannushi]]'' had been on the island. Every year, the two lighthouses built by Seinensha on the island are inspected and serviced, and during this time a yearly festival occurs, and prayers are issued for safe passage. In 2006, Seinensha donated the lighthouses to the government and they are now a national property administered by the [[Japan Coast Guard]].
In March 2004, several Chinese activists illegally landed on the island. Seinensha reported the incident to the [[Okinawa Police]], who arrested the activists and made a damage report.<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan, China out of step in handling of fishing boat collision incident |url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/perspectives/news/20100921p2a00m0na002000c.html |accessdate=15 October 2010 |newspaper=Mainichi Daily News |date=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923170330/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/perspectives/news/20100921p2a00m0na002000c.html |archivedate=September 23, 2010 }}</ref> Afterwards, Seinensha rebuilt the ''hokora'' and erected a plinth with the words "Senkaku Jinja" written on it. The ''hokora'' and plinth are built of solid granite.
== References == {{reflist}}
]] ]]
